create a dataset for Polish fluency measures only

fluency_pl <-  allData %>%
  select (DflR_pl, Retracing_pl, Repetitions_pl, Pauses_pl, Filled_pauses_pl, Breakdown_pl, Repair_pl, Phonationtime_pl, Mean_Length_of_Run_pl, Speechrate_pl, ArtR_pl, ASD_pl)

filter dataset: remove participants with missing values

fluency_pl_1 <- na.omit(fluency_pl)

# Choosing measures for PCA and creating datasets.

As some of the measures tap into the same areas, they correlate strongly. For example, Articulation Rate (ArtR) and ASD - cor=-0.98. Dysfluencies (DflR) are a sum of Breakdown and Repair, and Breakdown is a sum of Pauses and Filled pauses, while Repair is a sum of Repetations an Retracing. Speech Rate and Mean Length of Run are both composite measures that encompass speed and dysfluencies and are strongly correlated. I will remove storngly correlated measures for this analysis, which meanse I will run 3 separte PCAs - the first one looking at Speed and all dysfluencies only, which is based on the Speech Production Model - Levelt 89 (Art R and DflR) - the second one with Speed, Breakdown and Repair following Tavakoli and Skehan’s division. Then I will look at the most granual approach - I will look at speed and all aspects of dysfleuncies that we coded for separately.

#speed and all dysfluencies only:

fluency_pl_2components <-  fluency_pl_1 %>%
  select (DflR_pl, ArtR_pl)

#speed, breakdown, repair:

fluency_pl_3components <- fluency_pl_1 %>%
  select (Breakdown_pl, ArtR_pl, Repair_pl)


#fluency 

fluency_pl_5components <- fluency_pl_1 %>%
  select (ArtR_pl, Filled_pauses_pl, Pauses_pl, Retracing_pl, Repetitions_pl)


#speed, breakdown, repair and composite meausures:

fluency_pl_TavShcomposite <- fluency_pl_1 %>%
  select (Breakdown_pl, ArtR_pl, Repair_pl, Speechrate_pl, Mean_Length_of_Run_pl)

#PCA for 2 components:

scaling the data [purpose of scaling is to standardize the variance across variables] and running PCA

pca_pl_2 <- prcomp(fluency_pl_2components, center = TRUE,scale. = TRUE)

look at proportion of variance

summary(pca_pl_2)

var_explained_pl_2 <- pca_pl_2$sdev^2 / sum(pca_pl_2$sdev^2)

# Choosing measures for PCA and creating datasets.

As some of the measures tap into the same areas, they correlate strongly. For example, Articulation Rate (ArtR) and ASD - cor=-0.98. Dysfluencies (DflR) are a sum of Breakdown and Repair, and Breakdown is a sum of Pauses and Filled pauses, while Repair is a sum of Repetations an Retracing. Speech Rate and Mean Length of Run are both composite measures that encompass speed and dysfluencies and are strongly correlated. I will remove storngly correlated measures for this analysis, which meanse I will run 3 separte PCAs - the first one looking at Speed and all dysfluencies only, which is based on the Speech Production Model - Levelt 89 (Art R and DflR) - the second one with Speed, Breakdown and Repair following Tavakoli and Skehan’s division. Then I will look at the most granual approach - I will look at speed and all aspects of dysfleuncies that we coded for separately.

#fluency 

fluency_en_5components <- fluency_en_1 %>%
  select (ArtR_en, Filled_pauses_en, Pauses_en, Retracing_en, Repetitions_en)


#speed, breakdown, repair and composite meausures:

fluency_en_TavShcomposite <- fluency_en_1 %>%
  select (Breakdown_en, ArtR_en, Repair_en, Speechrate_en, Mean_Length_of_run_en)
